g) \n\n(a) MNLI\n\n![Refer to caption](x6.png) \n\n(b) GSM8k\n\n![Refer to caption](x7.png) \n\n(c) XSum\n\nFigure 3:  Comparison of different alternating step T𝑇Titalic\\_T used in LoftQ. T=0𝑇0T=0italic\\_T = 0 indicates we use QLoRA method that initializes low-rank adapters by ([5](#S2.E5 \"5 ‣ 2.3 Low-Rank Adaptation ‣ 2 Background ‣ LoftQ: LoRA-Fine-Tuning-Aware Quantization for Large Language Models\")). T=1,5,10𝑇\n\n1510T=1,5,10italic\\_T = 1 , 5 , 10 indicates we use different T𝑇Titalic\\_T for LoftQ described in Algorithm [1](#alg1 \"Algorithm 1 ‣ 3.2 Alternating Optimization ‣ 3 Method ‣ LoftQ: LoRA-Fine-Tuning-Aware Quantization for Large Language Models\"). Left: Uniform 2-bit DeBERTaV3-base. Middle: NF4 2-bit LLAMA-2-13b. Right: NF4 BART-large.\n\n## 5 Discussion\n\nStart with quantization or SVD in the alternating optimization? An alternative algorithm to the alternating optimization is that we first obtain the low-rank approximation At,Bt\n\nsubscript𝐴𝑡subscript𝐵𝑡A\\_{t},B\\_{t}italic\\_A start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_t end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic\\_B start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_t end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT and then obtain the quantized weight Qtsubscript𝑄𝑡Q\\_{t}italic\\_Q start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic\\_t end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT by switching Line 3 and Line 4 in Algorithm [1](#alg1 \"Algorithm 1 ‣ 3.2 Alternating Optimization ‣ 3 Method ‣ LoftQ: LoRA-Fine-Tuning-Aware Quantization for Large Language Models\"). We note this is a valid alternative method as both still jointly minimize the objective in ([6](#S3.E6 \"6 ‣ 3.1 LoRA-Aware Quantization ‣ 3 Method ‣ LoftQ: LoRA-Fine-Tuning-Aware Quantization for Large Language Models\")). Table [6](#S5.T6 \"Table 6 ‣ 5 Discussion ‣ LoftQ: LoRA-Fine-Tuning-Aware Quantization for Large Language Models\") summarizes the performance of this alternative method. It is noteworthy that the alternative method still outperforms QLoRA significantly, even though it is worse than the primary version. This observation underscores