TSUBSCRIPT italic\\_i end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT.\n\nSince the significant reduction of bit-width leads to decreased representation capability, the entropy of the quantized weight is far less than that of the original counterpart. For example, the number of representation candidates for a 4-bit quantized weight reduces 4096×4096\\times4096 × compared to its original 16-bit (FP16) counterpart, and the upper bound of information entropy ℋ⁢(𝒘^FP16)ℋsuperscript^𝒘FP16\\mathcal{H}(\\hat{\\boldsymbol{w}}^{\\text{FP16}})caligraphic\\_H ( over^ start\\_ARG bold\\_italic\\_w end\\_ARG start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT FP16 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) in Eq. ([6](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#S3.E6 \"Equation 6 ‣ 3.2.1 Degeneration of Quantized LLMs ‣ 3.2 Information Calibration Quantization ‣ 3 The Rise of IR-QLoRA ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\")) is correspondingly reduced 4×4\\times4 × (4 for 4-bit vs. 16 for 16-bit), meaning a significant degradation of information in the quantity and quality. Thus, prioritizing information recovery within low-bit weights is crucial for enhancing quantized LLMs.\n\n#### 3.2.2 Information Calibration Quantization for Representation Recovery\n\nTo mitigate the degeneration caused by information loss for the quantized LLMs, we introduce an Information Calibration Quantization (ICQ) technique for LLMs (as Figure [2](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#S3.F2 \"Figure 2 ‣ 3.1 Preliminaries ‣ 3 The Rise of IR-QLoRA ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\")), which applies the fine-grained information maximization of quantized weights to improve the accuracy.\n\nWe first introduce a calibration constant τ𝜏\\tauitalic\\_τ to the quantizer, liberating its flexibility to retain information fully. The quantization process it engages in can be expressed as follows:\n\n|  |  |\n| --- | --- |\n| 𝒘^NF⁢k=NF⁢k⁢(𝒘−τs).superscript^𝒘NF𝑘NF𝑘𝒘𝜏𝑠\\hat{\\boldsymbol{w}}^{\\text{NF}k}={\\text{NF}{k}}\\l