EC}}(\\boldsymbol{x})=\\boldsymbol{y}^{\\prime}\\_{\\text{ICQ}}+\\alpha U\\_{2}% \\circ U\\_{1}(\\boldsymbol{x}).bold\\_italic\\_y = bold\\_italic\\_y start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ′ end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ICQ end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT + italic\\_α italic\\_U start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT IEC end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold\\_italic\\_x ) = bold\\_italic\\_y start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ′ end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ICQ end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT + italic\\_α italic\\_U start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∘ italic\\_U start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold\\_italic\\_x ) . | (15) |\n\nAppendix [A.2](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A1.SS2 \"A.2 Details about Pipeline ‣ Appendix A Details about IR-QLoRA ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\") discusses the efficiency of IEC, which can be merged into LoRA to avoid additional inference costs.\n\nThe IEC propagates the input with elasticity dimension changing, thus allowing the matrix in LoRA to directly access and utilize the original information extracted by the quantized LLM projection. Moreover, the parameter-free IEC can seem diversified compared with the parametric matrix multiplication of LoRA, further enhancing the information representation of quantized LLMs.\n\n## 4 Experiment\n\nWe extensively evaluate the accuracy and efficiency of our proposed IR-QLoRA. Our IR-QLoRA is established upon the LLaMA (Touvron et al., [2023a](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib39)) and LLaMA2 (Touvron et al., [2023b](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib40)) families (7B, 13B, 30B, and 65B), and constructs parameter-efficient finetuning on Alpaca (Taori et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib38)) and Flan v2 (Longpre et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib32)) datasets. The Massively Multitask Language Understanding (MMLU) (Hendrycks et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib19)) and CommonsenseQA benchmarks(e.g.HellaSwag (Zellers et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib45)), PIQA (Bisk et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib3))) are applied for evaluation. For experiment settings (Dettmers et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib12); Xu et al., [2023b](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib44); Kim et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib25); Frantar et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib15)), we follow the settings of comparison methods reported in their publications or official code for fair comparison. All our experiments are conducted on Nvidia Tesla A100 GPUs. Detailed experiment settings and results are presented in Appendix [B](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A2 \"Appendix B Experiment Settings ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\") and Appendix [C](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A3 \"Appendix C Experiment Results ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\"), respectively.\n\n \n\nTable 1: Accuracy (%) comparison of LLaMA on the MMLU finetuned on the Alpaca dataset\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Method | #Bit | MMLU |\n| Hums. | STEM | Social | Other | Avg. |\n| LLaMA-7B | 16 | 33.3 | 29.8 | 37.8 | 38.0 | 34.6 |\n| \\hdashline[0.5pt/2pt] PEQA | 4 | 34.9 | 28.9 | 37.5 | 40.1 | 34.8 |\n| NormalFloat | 4 | 33.1 | 30.6 | 38.8 | 38.8 | 35.1 |\n| QLoRA w/ GPTQ | 4 | 33.8 | 31.3 | 37.4 | 42.2 | 36.0 |\n| QLoRA | 4 | 36.1 | 31.9 | 42.0 | 44.5 | 38.4 |\n| QA-LoRA | 4 | 36.6 | 32.4 | 44.8 | 44.9 | 39.4 |\n| IR-QLoRA | 4 | 38.6 | 34.6 | 45.2 | 45.5 | 40.8 |\n| LLaMA-13B | 16 | 40.6 | 36.7 | 48.9 | 48.0 | 43.3 |\n| \\hdashline[0.5pt/2pt] NormalFloat | 4 | 43.0 | 34.5 | 51.8 | 51.4 | 45.0 |\n| PEQA | 4 | 43.0 | 37.7 | 53.6 | 49.0 | 45.0 |\n| QLoRA | 4 | 45.4 | 37.4 | 55.7 | 54.3 | 48.0 |\n| QLoRA w/ GPTQ | 4 | 48.4 | 38.3 | 54.9 | 55.2 | 49.2 |\n| QA-LoRA | 4 | 48.4 | 38.3 | 54.9 | 55.2 | 