iverse natural language understanding tasks and are established as a prominent paradigm in this field (Chang et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib5); Devlin et al., [2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib13); Zhao et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib47); Huang & Chang, [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib22)). Recent noteworthy instances of LLMs encompass OpenAI’s GPT family (Brown et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib4)) and Meta’s LLaMA and LLaMA2 families (Touvron et al., [2023a](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib39), [b](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib40)). Nonetheless, the exceptional performance of these LLMs is contingent upon extensive parameters and computational resources. Notably, the PaLM-540B model boasts an impressive 540 billion parameters (Chowdhery et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib7)), underscoring the substantial computational demands. This reality poses substantial challenges to deploying LLMs in settings with limited resources. Consequently, the research of the compression technologies for LLMs has gained prominence as a critical area of research.\n\nCompression of LLMs. Existing compression technologies of LLMs include pruning, distillation, low-rank decomposition, and low-bit quantization (Ganesh et al., [2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib16); Zhu et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib48); Chitty-Venkata et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib6)). Pruning removes redundant parameters in LLMs structurally or unstructuredly (Frantar & Alistarh, [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib14); Zhang et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib46); Sun et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib37)). Distillation enables the compressed student LLMs to learn from intermediate features or predictions of a larger teacher model (Gu et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib18); Huang et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib23); Agarwal et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib1); Li et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib27); Jiang et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib24)). Low-rank decomposition saves computation by decomposing the weight of LLMs into smaller matrices with significantly reduced dimensions (Xu et al., [2023a](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib43)). Different from the above technologies that mainly reduce the number of parameters (weights and/or activations), quantization aims to compress the LLMs from 16-bit floating-point to lower bit-widths to mitigate the storage and computation.\n\nQuantization of LLMs. Since compression is from a generic bit-width perspective, quantization has become a popular method to obtain efficient LLMs (Frantar et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib15); Xiao et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib42)). The most common practice is directly performing post-training quantization on pre-trained LLMs and optimizing quantizers through calibration (Lin et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib29); Lee et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib26); Shao et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib36); Dettmers et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib11)), which usually results in non-negligible degradation. Some quantization-aware training methods finetune the parameters of quantized LLMs to improve accuracy (Liu et al., [2023b](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib31); Kim et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib25)), while the computational burden brought is significantly expensive. The LoRA-finetuning quantization of LLMs emerges to achieve a balanced trade-off between computational cost and accuracy (Dettmers et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib12); Xu et al., [2023b](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib44); Li et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib28)), where LLMs are first quantized and then finetuned with a parameter-efficient LoRA. However, existing quantized LLMs with LoRA are still far from ideal in accuracy.\n\n### A.2 Details about Pipeline\n\nIn this section, we demonstrate the application of Information Calibration Quantization (ICQ) and Information Elastic Connection (IEC) in our IR-QLoRA in detail when we quantizing the LLMs.\n\n \n\nAlgorithm 1  The weight search process within each block in IR-QLoRA\n\nInput: Block Weight 𝒘𝒘\\boldsymbol{w}bold\\_italic\\_w, hypermeters λ,σ,n\n\n𝜆𝜎𝑛\\lambda,\\sigma,nitalic\\_λ , italic\\_σ , italic\\_n\n\nOutput: Calibration constant τ1FP⁢8,τ2FP⁢16\n\nsuperscriptsubscript𝜏1FP8superscriptsubscript𝜏2FP16\\tau\\_{1}^{\\text{FP}8},\\tau\\_{2}^{\\text{FP}16}italic\\_τ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT FP 8 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , italic\\_τ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT FP 16 end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT\n\nInitialize τ0=quantile12⁡(𝒘),ℋ∗=0formulae-sequencesubscript𝜏0subscriptquantile12𝒘superscriptℋ0\\tau\\_{0}=\\operatorname{quantile}\\_{\\frac{1}{2}}\\left(\\boldsymbol{w}\\right),% \\mathcal{H}^{\\*}=0italic\\_τ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT = roman\\_quantile start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT divide start\\_ARG 1 end\\_ARG start\\_ARG 2 end\\_ARG end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold\\_italic\\_w ) , caligraphic\\_H start\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end\\_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = 0\n\nfor τ𝜏\\tauitalic\\_τ in Linspace⁡(τ0−λ⁢σ,τ0+λ⁢σ,λ⁢σn)Linspacesubscript𝜏0𝜆𝜎subscript𝜏0𝜆𝜎𝜆𝜎𝑛\\operatorname{Linspace}(\\tau\\_{0}-\\lambda\\sigma,\\tau\\_{0}+\\lambda\\sigma,\\frac{% \\lambda\\sigma}{n})roman\\_Linspace ( italic\\_τ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT - italic\\_λ italic\\_σ , italic\\_τ start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT 0 end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT + italic\\_λ italic\\_σ 