ose Alpaca (Taori et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib38)) and FLAN v2 (Longpre et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib32)) as our finetuning datasets. Alpaca contains 52K instruction-following data generated from text-davinci-003 (GPT 3.5) (Wang et al., [2022](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib41)). Flan v2 is a collection of 1,836 tasks combining the mixture with CoT, Muffin, T0-SF, and NIV2.\n\n### B.2 NormalFloat Quantization\n\nQuantile Quantization (Dettmers et al., [2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib10)) is an information-theoretically optimal data type that ensures each quantization bin has an equal number of values from the input tensor. Essentially, it distributes the data evenly across the available quantization levels, leading to efficient and balanced utilization of the quantized representation.\n\nBuilding on Quantile Quantization, NormalFloat (NF) Quantization (Dettmers et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib12)) introduces the quantization principle that the weights conform to a zero-centered normal distribution. By converting all weights into a fixed distribution, their distribution is fully adapted to the range of the specified data type. Then the quantile constant can be calculated. Following the processing steps in QLoRA (Dettmers et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib12)), we can get different quantized points according to different quantized bit widths. Table [11](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A2.T11 \"Table 11 ‣ B.2 NormalFloat Quantization ‣ Appendix B Experiment Settings ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\")-[13](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A2.T13 \"Table 13 ‣ B.2 NormalFloat Quantization ‣ Appendix B Experiment Settings ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\") shows the NF quantization for 2-4 bits, respectively. Note that we use symmetrical settings in NF2 to prevent excessive deviation of information.\n\n \n\nTable 11: The exact values of the NormalFloat 2-bit (NF2) data type\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Index | Value | Index | Value |\n| 0 | -1.0 | 2 | 0.2525685131549835 |\n| 1 | -0.25256848335266113 | 3 | 1.0 |\n\n  \n\nTable 12: The exact values of the NormalFloat 3-bit (NF3) data type\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Index | Value | Index | Value |\n| 0 | -1.0 | 4 | 0.16093020141124725 |\n| 1 | -0.4786292016506195 | 5 | 0.33791524171829224 |\n| 2 | -0.217141792178154 | 6 | 0.5626170039176941 |\n| 3 | 0.0 | 7 | 1.0 |\n\n  \n\nTable 13: The exact values of the NormalFloat 4-bit (NF4) data type\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Index | Value | Index | Value |\n| 0 | -1.0 | 8 | 0.07958029955625534 |\n| 1 | -0.6961928009986877 | 9 | 0.16093020141124725 |\n| 2 | -0.5250730514526367 | 10 | 0.24611230194568634 |\n| 3 | -0.39491748809814453 | 11 | 0.33791524171829224 |\n| 4 | -0.28444138169288635 | 12 | 0.44070982933044434 |\n| 5 | -0.18477343022823334 | 13 | 0.5626170039176941 |\n| 6 | -0.09105003625154495 | 14 | 0.7229568362236023 |\n| 7 | 0.0 | 15 | 1.0 |\n\n  \n\nTable 14: Examples for each the evaluation datasets\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Dataset | Question | Answer |\n| MMLU | Which of the following factors is associated with a decreased risk of Alzheimer’s? | B |\n| (A) Being African or Hispanic American | (B) Eating fish |\n| (C) A lower level of education | (D) Being married |\n| HellaSwag | A man is sitting on a roof. he | D |\n| (A) is using wrap to wrap a pair of skis. | (B) is ripping level tiles off. |\n| (C) is holding a rubik’s cube. | (D) starts pulling up roofing on a roof. |\n| PIQA | How do I ready a guinea pig cage for it’s new occupants? | A |\n| (A) Provide the guinea pig with a cage full of a few inches of bedding made of ripped paper strips, you will also need to supply it with a water bottle and a food dish. |\n| (B) Provide the guinea pig with a cage full of a few inches of bedding made of ripped jeans material, you will also need to supply it with a water bottle and a food dish. |\n| WinoGrande | John moved the couch from the garage to the backyard to create space. The \\_ is small. | A |\n| (A) garage | (B) backyard |\n| ARC-Easy | Which factor will most likely cause a person to develop a fever? | B |\n| (A) a leg muscle relaxing after exercise | (B) a bacterial population in the bloodstream |\n| (C) several viral particles on the skin | (D) carbohydrates being digested in the stomach |\n| ARC-Challenge | George wants to warm his hands quickly by rubbing them. Which skin surface will produce the most heat? | A |\n| (A) dry palms | (B) wet palms |\n| (C) palms covered with oil | (D) palms covered with lotion |\n| BoolQ | Phantom pain sensations are described as perceptions that an individual experiences relating to a limb or an organ that is not physically part of the body. Limb loss is a result of either removal by amputation or congenital limb deficiency. However, phantom limb sensations can also occur following nerve avulsion or spinal cord injury. Is pain experienced in a missing body part or paralyzed area? | B |\n| (A) True | (B) False |\n| OpenBookQA | A magnet will stick to | A |\n| (A) a belt buckle | (B) a wooden table, |\n| (C) a plastic cup | (D) a paper plate |\n\n### B.3 Evaluation Metrics\n\nFollowing QLoRA (Dettmers et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib12)) and QA-LoRA (Xu et al., [2023b](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib44)), we evaluate language understanding capabilities of the LLMs on Massively Multitask Language Understanding (MMLU) benchmark (Hendrycks et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib19)) and commonsense reasoning ability on several Common Sense QA datasets.\n\nMMLU includes 57 language tasks, including humanities (Hums.), STEM, social science, etc. We utilize the MMLU evaluation script and prompts as outlined in  (Hendrycks et al., [2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib20)). Common Sense QA datasets includes HellaSwag (Zellers et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib45)), PIQA (Bisk et al., [2020](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib3)), WinoGrande (Sakaguchi et al., [2021](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib35)), ARC (Clark et al., [2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib9)), BoolQ (Clark et al., [2019](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib8)), and OpenBookQA (Mihaylov et al., [2018](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib33)). We adopt lm-evalharness (Gao et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib17)) to produce the Common Sense QA results. Table [14](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A2.T14 \"Table 14 ‣ B.2 NormalFloat Quantization ‣ Appendix B Experiment Settings ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\") provides examples of each evaluation dataset. Given the multiple-choice (MC) nature of these tasks, accuracy is selected as the primary metric for evaluation.\n\n### B.4 Implementation Details\n\nAll experiments are conducted on Tesla A100 GPUs. Following (Dettmers et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib12)), we apply the double quantization mechanism, and set the block size is 64 for quantization and 256 for double quantization. Regarding LoRA parameters, we set r=64𝑟64r=64italic\\_r = 64, α=16𝛼16\\alpha=16italic\\_α = 16, and LoRA dropout of 0.1 for models up to 13B and 0.05 for 33B and 65B models. We employ the paged AdamW optimizer with a beta2 value of 0.999, and a learning rate of 2e-4 for models up to 13B and 1e-4 for 33B and 65B models., limiting the maximum gradient norm to 0.3 and adopting a constant learning rate strategy. Fine-tuning was executed for 10,000 and 20,000 steps on the Alpaca and FLAN v2 datasets, respectively, utilizing a batch size 16.\n\n## Appendix C Experiment Results\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/5620030/figures/Query_Projection_Linear_Entropy.png)\n\n(a) Query Linear Projection\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/5620030/figures/Value_Projection_Linear_Entropy.png)\n\n(b) Value Linear Projection\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/5620030/figures/Output_Projection_Linear_Entropy.png)\n\n(c) Output Linear Projection\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/5620030/figures/MLP_Up_Projection_Linear_Entropy.png)\n\n(d) MLP Up Linear Projection\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/5620030/figures/MLP_Down_Projection_Linear_Entropy.png)\n\n(e) MLP Down Linear Projection\n\n![Refer to caption](extracted/5620030/figures/MLP_Gate_Projection_Linear_Entropy.png)\n\n(f) MLP Gate Linear Projection\n\nFigure 5: Entropy comparison of linear projections in 4-bit LLaMA-7B\n\n \n\n### C.1 Weight Visualization\n\nIn addition to the linear projection for Key mentioned earlier, we also compute the entropy of quantized weights in various other types of layers, as illustrated in Figure [5](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A3.F5 \"Figure 5 ‣ Appendix C Experiment Results ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\"). This observation confirms that ICQ effectively boosts the information entropy of weights and augments the mutual information between the weights of quantized and original LLMs, consequently alleviating the constraints on representational capacity imposed by quantization.\n\n### C.2 Efficiency Ablation\n\nWe counted the number of parameters and training time for different sizes of LLaMA, as shown in Table [15](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A3.T15 \"Table 15 ‣ C.2 Efficiency Ablation ‣ Appendix C Experiment Results ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\"). It is evident that IEC introduces a minimal number of additional parameters and does not increase the training time. In the case of ICQ, a small number of extra parameters are introduced, and the increase in training time is only incurred once, as the results can be efficiently cached after ICQ is applied. Thus, IR-QLoRA maintains nearly the same efficiency as Vanilla.\n\n \n\nTable 15: Efficiency ablation on the different sizes of LLaMA\n\n|  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Method | #Bit | #Params(GB) | Time(h) |\n| 7B | 13B | 30B | 65B | 7B | 13B | 30B | 65B |\n| LLaMA | 16 | 12.55 | 24.24 | 60.59 | 121.60 | - | - | - | - |\n| \\hdashline[0.5pt/2pt] Vanilla | 4 | 2.34 | 4.13 | 9.41 | 18.02 | 15.33 | 26.18 | 42.71 | 118.97 |\n| ICQ | 4 | 2.39 | 4.22 | 9.65 | 18.50 | 15.40 | 26.26 | 43.07 | 119.38 |\n| IEC | 4 | 2.34 | 4.13 | 9.41 | 18.02 | 15.33 | 26.18 | 42.71 | 118.97 |\n| IR-QLoRA | 4 | 2.39 | 4.22 | 9.65 | 18.50 | 15.40 | 26.26 | 43.07 | 119.38 |\n\n### C.3 Case Study\n\nThis section offers a qualitative analysis that contrasts the performance of our IR-QLoRA model with that of QLoRA within the domain of LLM quantization. Utilizing prompts from the Stanford Alpaca dataset (Taori et al., [2023](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#bib.bib38)) for text generation, we indicate definitive answers in blue and unexpected responses in red for clarity. Our qualitative assessment accentuates the enhanced capabilities of IR-QLoRA in intricate understanding and text generation quality, compared to the QLoRA baseline.\n\nCognitive Reasoning. The cognitive reasoning aptitude of IR-QLoRA has shown notable advancement. When tasked with challenges that require logical deduction and computational acumen, such as those presented in arithmetic case studies and family relationship inference, as illustrated in Table [16](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A3.T16 \"Table 16 ‣ C.3 Case Study ‣ Appendix C Experiment Results ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\"), IR-QLoRA demonstrates a commendable level of proficiency. These results underscore its inherent reasoning capabilities and shed light on the potential for cognitive reasoning in quantized, smaller-scale models like QLoRA-7B. Both IR-QLoRA-7B and IR-QLoRA-13B provided correct answers and demonstrated a capacity to explain their reasoning to a certain degree. In contrast, QLoRA-7B failed to answer correctly.\n\nText Generation Quality. IR-QLoRA demonstrates substantial improvements in the coherence and fluency of generated text. When tasked with composing narratives for various scenarios, from mundane daily activities to complex extraterrestrial interactions, as cataloged in Table [16](https://arxiv.org/html/2402.05445v2#A3.T16 \"Table 16 ‣ C.3 Case Study ‣ Appendix C Experiment Results ‣ Accurate LoRA-Finetuning Quantization of LLMs via Information Retention\"), IR-QLoRA invariably outshines QLoRA. Both IR-QLoRA-7B and IR-QLoRA-13B demonstrate a remarkable ability to generate narratives with consistent themes and create more comprehensive stories. In contrast, QLoRA-7B often falters by misinterpreting the subject matter or producing narratives that lack completeness.\n\n \n\nTable 16: Case study for text generation outputs\n\n|  |\n| --- |\n| [1] Input: Alice has 15 apples. She buys 10 more from the market and then gives 7 apples to her friend. How many apples does Alice have now? |\n| Answer: Alice have 18 apples now. |\n| Model | Output |\n| QLoRA-7B | 22 |\n| IR-QLoRA-7B (ours) | Alice now has 18 apples. |\n| QLoRA-13B | Alice had 15 apples. Alice buys 10 more apples. Alice has 15 + 10 = 25 apples. Alice gives 7 apples to her friend. Alice has 25 - 7 = 18 apples. |\n| IR-QLoRA-13B (ours) | Alice started with 15 apples and then bought 10 apples from the market, so her total apples inventory is now 25 apples (15 + 10 = 25). Then she gave 7 apples to her friend, so her total apples inventory is now 18 apples (25 - 7 = 18). Alice now has 18 apples. |\n| [2] Input: If Thomas is Joseph’s son, what is Thomas to Joseph’s father? |\n| Answer: Thomas is Joseph’s father’s grandson |\n| Model | Output |\n| QLoRA-7B | nephew |\n| IR-QLoRA-7B (ours) | Thomas is grandson of Joseph’s father. |\n| QLoRA-13B | grandson