an\\_B |\n| 7⁢B7B7\\mathrm{~{}B}7 roman\\_B | 4096 | 11008 | 32 | 32 | 150K | 19.7⁢B19.7B19.7\\mathrm{~{}B}19.7 roman\\_B |\n\nFor all methods on each size of models (from 60M to 1B), we tune their favorite learning rate from a set of {0.01,0.005,0.001,0.0005,0.0001}0.010.0050.0010.00050.0001\\{0.01,0.005,0.001,0.0005,0.0001\\}{ 0.01 , 0.005 , 0.001 , 0.0005 , 0.0001 }, and the best learning rate is chosen based on the validation perplexity. We find GaLore is insensitive to hyperparameters and tends to be stable with the same learning rate across different model sizes. For all models, GaLore use the same hyperparameters, including the learning rate of 0.010.010.010.01, scale factor α𝛼\\alphaitalic\\_α of 0.250.250.250.25, and the subspace change frequency of T𝑇Titalic\\_T of 200200200200. We note that since α𝛼\\alphaitalic\\_α can be viewed as a fractional learning rate, most of the modules (e.g., multi-head attention and feed-forward layers) in LLaMA models have the actual learning rate of 0.00250.00250.00250.0025. This is, still, a relatively large stable learning rate compared to the full-rank baseline, which usually uses a learning rate ≤0.001absent0.001\\leq 0.001≤ 0.001 to avoid spikes in the training loss.\n\n### B.2 Memory Estimates\n\nAs the GPU memory usage for a specific component is hard to measure directly, we estimate the memory usage of the weight parameters and optimizer states for each method on different model sizes. The estimation is based on the number of original parameters and the number of low-rank parameters, trained by BF16 format. For example, for a 60M model, LoRA (r=128𝑟128r=128italic\\_r = 128) requires 42.742.742.742.7M parameters on low-rank adaptors and 60⁢M60𝑀60M60 italic\\_M parameters on the original weights, resulting in a memory cost of 0.200.200.200.20G for weight parameters and 0.170.170.170.17G for optimizer states. Table [6](https://arxiv.org/html/2403.03507v1#A2.T6 \"Table 6 ‣ B.2 Memory Estimates ‣ Appendix B Details of Pre